<li id="cite_note-Rashed-19"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Rashed_19-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFRashed2007">Rashed, R. (2007). "The Celestial Kinematics of Ibn al-Haytham". <i><a href="/w/index.php?title=Arabic_Sciences_and_Philosophy&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Arabic Sciences and Philosophy (page does not exist)">Arabic Sciences and Philosophy</a></i> (<a href="/wiki/Cambridge_University_Press" title="Cambridge University Press">Cambridge University Press</a>) <b>17</b> (1): 7–55 [19]. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<span class="neverexpand"><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1017%2FS0957423907000355" class="external text" title="http://dx.doi.org/10.1017%2FS0957423907000355" rel="nofollow">10.1017/S0957423907000355</a></span>.  "In his optics <i>the smallest parts of light</i>, as he calls them, retain only properties that can be treated by geometry and verified by experiment; they lack all sensible qualities except energy.".</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+Celestial+Kinematics+of+Ibn+al-Haytham&amp;rft.jtitle=%5B%5BArabic+Sciences+and+Philosophy%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=Rashed&amp;rft.aufirst=R.&amp;rft.au=Rashed%2C+R.&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.volume=17&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=7%E2%80%9355+%5B19%5D&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BCambridge+University+Press%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=info:doi/10.1017%2FS0957423907000355&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Photon"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
